{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DeDQN7cKd3b1kAN7Yz1NZ7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the problem. Looking at the configmap:\n\n```yaml\ncluster.name: es-cluster\nnode.name: ${POD_NAME}\nnode.roles: [ master, data, ingest ]\nnetwork.host: 0.0.0.0\ndiscovery.seed_hosts:\n  - es-cluster-0.es-cluster\n  - es-cluster-1.es-cluster\n  - es-cluster-2.es-cluster\nnode.store.allow_mmap: false\n```\n\nThe issue is that `cluster.initial_master_nodes` is **missing** from the config. \n\nThis setting is critical for bootstrapping a new Elasticsearch cluster—without it, nodes can't form a quorum because they don't know which nodes are eligible to be initial masters. The \"master not discovered yet\" error occurs because `discovery.seed_hosts` only tells nodes where to find others, but `cluster.initial_master_nodes` is what actually designates which nodes can participate in the initial election. For Elasticsearch 7.x, you need to add `cluster.initial_master_nodes: [\"es-cluster-0\", \"es-cluster-1\", \"es-cluster-2\"]` to the configuration.\n\nSince this is a bootstrap-only setting that becomes dangerous once the cluster is formed, the approach is to add it to the configmap, restart the pods to let the cluster form and elect a master, then remove the setting once the cluster is healthy and do another rolling restart to ensure stability without it.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2038,"cache_read_input_tokens":36318,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2038},"output_tokens":34,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c1aeb080-c4bc-49be-a153-9f9d3b60a97a","uuid":"cac59542-17bc-4783-b0be-8eafaecf5c35","request_id":"req_011CcRCkhNufyv5LzUpzujrL"}
